WEBVTT

00:05.246 --> 00:08.180
[dramatic music]

00:08.215 --> 00:15.118
♪

00:15.153 --> 00:16.154
- Ow.
[bleep].

00:16.188 --> 00:19.674
I just cut myself,
but I'm not tapping out.

00:19.709 --> 00:24.058
- It is time to make
this shelter uber insulated.

00:24.093 --> 00:26.060
Arctic winter is no joke.

00:26.095 --> 00:27.337
♪

00:32.756 --> 00:33.964
♪

00:33.999 --> 00:36.346
- Holy [bleep].
I got a fire.

00:36.381 --> 00:38.348
♪

00:38.383 --> 00:39.729
[bleep].

00:39.763 --> 00:46.770
♪

00:50.360 --> 00:53.053
male narrator: In "Alone's"
coldest location ever,

00:53.087 --> 00:56.504
ten participants
fight to survive the arctic.

00:56.539 --> 00:57.574
- The arctic
is one of the most

00:57.609 --> 00:59.093
physically demanding
places on Earth.

00:59.128 --> 01:01.164
- So freakin' cold right now.

01:01.199 --> 01:03.097
narrator: Battling
sub-zero temperatures...

01:03.132 --> 01:05.341
- This climate's harsh.
It's extreme.

01:05.375 --> 01:07.067
It's mean.
It's got teeth.

01:07.101 --> 01:09.345
- Get caught out here in
a whiteout, you're in trouble.

01:09.379 --> 01:10.587
narrator:
Vicious predators...

01:10.622 --> 01:12.520
- Just heard something big
moving back there.

01:12.555 --> 01:14.902
- Me against the wolverine
right now.

01:14.936 --> 01:16.179
narrator: And isolation.

01:16.214 --> 01:17.801
- There's nothing
to fill that void.

01:17.836 --> 01:19.941
It's just you left alone
with your thoughts.

01:19.976 --> 01:22.185
narrator:
How long will they endure?

01:22.220 --> 01:24.084
- [grunts]
- House is on fire.

01:24.118 --> 01:26.741
- I'm scared,
but I don't wanna tap.

01:26.776 --> 01:28.640
- This is the most
unforgiving landscape

01:28.674 --> 01:29.744
I've ever seen.

01:29.779 --> 01:31.988
narrator: The last one
standing wins.

01:32.022 --> 01:34.266
- This environment
will strip away

01:34.301 --> 01:36.268
everything and anything
you thought you had.

01:36.303 --> 01:39.996
♪

01:40.030 --> 01:42.999
[ominous music]

01:43.033 --> 01:50.040
♪

02:03.192 --> 02:05.746
- Last night my shelter
lit on fire.

02:05.780 --> 02:07.472
♪

02:07.506 --> 02:09.336
It caught some moss in a wall.

02:09.370 --> 02:11.234
And I saw it happen
and I tried to put it out

02:11.269 --> 02:13.650
before it got too bad
and I couldn't.

02:13.685 --> 02:16.860
That was my nice
closed-in fireplace.

02:16.895 --> 02:18.966
Didn't know light before.

02:19.000 --> 02:21.451
I knew it was a risk having
the moss higher up

02:21.486 --> 02:23.004
without having it covered
in clay,

02:23.039 --> 02:26.215
but it froze up before
I could get it all done.

02:26.249 --> 02:27.664
Man, it went quick last night.

02:27.699 --> 02:29.287
That whole wall was engulfed.

02:29.321 --> 02:31.841
I had to just start ripping
every part of it down.

02:31.875 --> 02:33.014
♪

02:33.049 --> 02:34.533
Mother-eff it.

02:34.568 --> 02:36.846
♪

02:36.880 --> 02:39.159
I did not need to be
doing this right now.

02:40.712 --> 02:42.300
♪

02:42.334 --> 02:43.818
I don't really have time
to [bleep] around

02:43.853 --> 02:46.062
and feel sorry for myself.

02:46.096 --> 02:48.996
My plan is,
I'm just gonna build this back

02:49.030 --> 02:50.687
pretty much the way I had it,

02:50.722 --> 02:52.689
but we're just not
gonna use moss.

02:52.724 --> 02:53.828
♪

02:53.863 --> 02:55.451
This reminds me of my grandpa.

02:55.485 --> 02:57.901
He was a tough, tough
son of a bitch.

02:57.936 --> 02:59.144
And he always told me,
he said:

02:59.179 --> 03:00.732
"Michelle, if somebody's
standing in front of you

03:00.766 --> 03:01.940
and they're causing you
problems,"

03:01.974 --> 03:03.666
he said,
"You just keep swinging.

03:03.700 --> 03:05.461
When there's nobody left
in front you,"

03:05.495 --> 03:07.532
he said, "then you can rest."

03:07.566 --> 03:09.844
That's kind of been
my motto for like,

03:09.879 --> 03:13.227
you know, you just
keep swinging every day.

03:13.262 --> 03:15.712
Ho, that's tough work, guys.

03:15.747 --> 03:18.163
I cut down a couple of
bigger trees

03:18.198 --> 03:21.442
with the hope I can fill in
the gaps

03:21.477 --> 03:23.582
that are gonna be left.

03:23.617 --> 03:26.792
Hopefully, I can get clay
and fill in all those spots,

03:26.827 --> 03:29.519
and I can avoid
any future fires.

03:29.554 --> 03:30.969
♪

03:31.003 --> 03:33.040
I knew that this would
be hard.

03:33.074 --> 03:37.217
I knew that it would be
a test of my limits.

03:37.251 --> 03:39.357
And I still came.

03:39.391 --> 03:42.498
You gotta find that strength
deep down inside ya.

03:42.532 --> 03:44.016
Could have called it
last night,

03:44.051 --> 03:46.156
but I curled up in
my sleeping bag

03:46.191 --> 03:48.228
and hung on, you know.

03:48.262 --> 03:51.231
[foreboding music]

03:51.265 --> 03:54.751
♪

03:54.786 --> 03:58.099
Having to rebuild set me back,
delaying everything

03:58.134 --> 04:00.723
and putting a real hitch in
my plans.

04:00.757 --> 04:03.001
There's still more work there
to be done.

04:03.035 --> 04:05.624
I just gotta chip away
at things.

04:05.659 --> 04:07.454
I'm having difficulties,
having setbacks,

04:07.488 --> 04:09.732
having challenges,
but that's just kinda how

04:09.766 --> 04:11.320
my life works anyway, you know.

04:11.354 --> 04:13.632
That's nothing new for me.

04:13.667 --> 04:15.634
♪

04:15.669 --> 04:18.361
Nothing ever seems easy for me.

04:18.396 --> 04:19.673
It always seems like
I'm struggling

04:19.707 --> 04:20.777
just to get ahead

04:20.812 --> 04:22.779
and get one foot in front of
the other one.

04:22.814 --> 04:25.057
♪

04:25.092 --> 04:27.853
Just keep swinging.

04:27.888 --> 04:30.856
[dark music]

04:30.891 --> 04:37.898
♪

04:48.080 --> 04:50.220
- Last night was crazy.

04:50.255 --> 04:51.808
Woke up, I believe I heard

04:51.843 --> 04:54.466
a moose running around
out there.

04:54.501 --> 04:57.642
Thought long and hard about
trying to get up and go out

04:57.676 --> 05:00.645
and take a shot,
but it's so noisy

05:00.679 --> 05:02.474
trying to get out of
your sleeping bag

05:02.509 --> 05:04.752
and get your clothes on
and all that.

05:04.787 --> 05:05.788
And once it sees you,

05:05.822 --> 05:07.099
then that would be like,
"Oh, man,"

05:07.134 --> 05:08.308
and blow up the spot.

05:09.930 --> 05:11.759
So today, I'm gonna see
where he went

05:11.794 --> 05:14.106
and kinda follow his tracks.

05:14.141 --> 05:17.420
♪

05:17.455 --> 05:18.594
I need to get a moose,

05:18.628 --> 05:20.078
because I feel like
this location

05:20.112 --> 05:23.046
provides me
really only with rabbits.

05:23.081 --> 05:25.842
Rabbits have so much protein
on 'em and so little fat,

05:25.877 --> 05:29.674
that you can eat 'em,
but not get enough energy.

05:29.708 --> 05:30.778
Fat is what you need,

05:30.813 --> 05:32.884
and it's the stuff of life
out here.

05:32.918 --> 05:35.542
Moose has got a ton of
delicious fat on it.

05:35.576 --> 05:37.613
[foliage ruffling]

05:37.647 --> 05:39.339
Oh, yes.

05:39.373 --> 05:41.410
Here are these fresh tracks.

05:42.480 --> 05:45.931
Slopping up the mud.

05:45.966 --> 05:49.107
I believe these are the ones
I heard last night.

05:49.141 --> 05:56.148
♪

05:57.426 --> 05:59.980
This is great.

06:00.014 --> 06:02.154
From the looks of the tracks,

06:02.189 --> 06:05.261
they follow this weed edge

06:05.295 --> 06:08.575
down to this
little mud bog thing here.

06:08.609 --> 06:10.473
♪

06:10.508 --> 06:14.650
See over there,
that's why I heard him.

06:14.684 --> 06:16.617
My shelter's right over there.

06:16.652 --> 06:18.516
♪

06:18.550 --> 06:20.966
Happy to see the moose
so close.

06:21.001 --> 06:24.176
Not every day you get
the chance like this.

06:24.211 --> 06:25.730
To be able to shoot a moose,

06:25.764 --> 06:27.697
especially one when
you really need it,

06:27.732 --> 06:29.423
it's, like, really exciting.

06:29.458 --> 06:34.359
I'm gonna go make a early
warning system for moose.

06:34.394 --> 06:35.429
♪

06:35.464 --> 06:40.054
So when I'm sitting over there
half dazed off...

06:40.089 --> 06:42.747
I might hear him coming first.

06:42.781 --> 06:45.439
So I took some of these cans
that I found

06:45.474 --> 06:48.304
and put some trip strings
around.

06:48.338 --> 06:49.339
♪

06:49.374 --> 06:50.444
I wanted to put it here,

06:50.479 --> 06:51.825
'cause I actually don't want it
to bang

06:51.859 --> 06:54.103
across the lot of rocks.

06:54.137 --> 06:56.519
I don't want it to actually
scare the moose

06:56.554 --> 06:58.003
or startle it.

06:58.038 --> 07:01.455
I just want it to flip over
that one--clink!

07:01.490 --> 07:05.701
And that'll be enough to
alert me to get my bow ready.

07:05.735 --> 07:07.565
Wish me luck.

07:07.599 --> 07:10.568
[tense music]

07:10.602 --> 07:17.609
♪

07:25.375 --> 07:27.516
- Check my mousetraps.

07:29.828 --> 07:31.830
No mouse.

07:31.865 --> 07:33.073
Let's check the other one.

07:34.523 --> 07:36.559
Come on, be a mouse.
Be a mouse.

07:36.594 --> 07:39.217
Please, please, please.

07:39.251 --> 07:40.805
Oh!

07:40.839 --> 07:42.151
It's set off.

07:43.808 --> 07:45.223
Come on.

07:47.018 --> 07:49.399
Yes!

07:49.434 --> 07:51.816
Hello, beautiful.

07:51.850 --> 07:55.302
Oh, my gosh.
I got a mouse.

07:55.336 --> 08:00.134
He's just frozen and squashed

08:00.169 --> 08:03.931
like crazy, but...

08:03.966 --> 08:08.798
I just...so grateful
for this little guy.

08:08.833 --> 08:12.422
♪

08:12.457 --> 08:13.665
I feel strong.

08:13.700 --> 08:17.013
I feel excited to be
here still.

08:17.048 --> 08:20.223
Overall, I feel good.

08:20.258 --> 08:22.329
Brunch.

08:22.363 --> 08:24.331
I feel pretty nervous.

08:24.365 --> 08:26.920
I mean, I'm not hungry.

08:26.954 --> 08:30.924
I've never gone to bed hungry,
I never wake up hungry.

08:30.958 --> 08:32.270
I'm gonna show you
how to prepare

08:32.304 --> 08:35.307
a blueberry mouse muffin.

08:35.342 --> 08:38.379
You take your mouse head,

08:38.414 --> 08:42.556
and you jam all of these
blueberries in there

08:42.591 --> 08:46.180
so that every bite literally is
a blueberry.

08:46.215 --> 08:49.598
And you don't have to taste
the mouse head.

08:49.632 --> 08:50.668
Like that.

08:51.841 --> 08:52.911
Stay on.

08:54.568 --> 08:57.537
[chewing]

08:59.953 --> 09:04.095
And then after it goes down,
you proceed...

09:04.129 --> 09:05.372
[groans]

09:05.406 --> 09:09.100
With another good dose
of blueberries...

09:10.550 --> 09:12.759
Just for the aftertaste.

09:15.658 --> 09:17.246
Mm.

09:17.280 --> 09:18.247
[sniffles]

09:18.281 --> 09:19.662
♪

09:19.697 --> 09:22.803
The mice are definitely
all over this area,

09:22.838 --> 09:24.943
but they're just small
and so I'd rather be

09:24.978 --> 09:27.118
working on bigger animals
right now.

09:27.152 --> 09:29.396
I feel like I'm actively
gonna seek out

09:29.430 --> 09:31.329
the squirrel that
lives near me.

09:31.363 --> 09:34.884
My body needs more calories
and energy to be able to

09:34.919 --> 09:37.818
walk farther to seek
other animals.

09:37.853 --> 09:38.888
♪

09:38.923 --> 09:39.889
[squeaking]

09:39.924 --> 09:41.719
I hear him.

09:41.753 --> 09:43.686
I actually hear him.

09:44.894 --> 09:46.240
[exhales]

09:46.275 --> 09:48.104
And he's right here.

09:49.105 --> 09:51.176
[squeaking]

09:51.211 --> 09:52.315
[bow vibrates]

09:52.350 --> 09:54.041
Ah.

09:54.076 --> 09:55.180
Whoa, buddy.
Whoa, buddy.

09:55.215 --> 09:56.941
Whoa, buddy.
Whoa.

09:56.975 --> 09:57.942
[squeaking]

09:57.976 --> 09:59.668
Oh, now.

09:59.702 --> 10:01.393
Where are you, little guy?

10:01.428 --> 10:02.705
♪

10:02.740 --> 10:05.708
[squeaking continues]

10:05.743 --> 10:09.609
♪

10:09.643 --> 10:11.093
I see him.

10:11.127 --> 10:12.922
♪

10:12.957 --> 10:14.027
Hey, buddy.

10:14.061 --> 10:15.891
[clicks tongue]

10:15.925 --> 10:18.410
There's so many branches
in the way.

10:18.445 --> 10:22.449
♪

10:26.729 --> 10:27.834
[bow vibrates]

10:27.868 --> 10:29.180
Oh, I got him.

10:30.457 --> 10:33.184
[grunting]

10:33.218 --> 10:34.772
Freaking got him.

10:36.532 --> 10:37.913
Sorry, buddy.

10:40.225 --> 10:43.781
Oh.
Oh, buddy.

10:44.920 --> 10:47.785
Oh.
Oh, no.

10:49.579 --> 10:51.305
Oh.

10:51.340 --> 10:54.308
[gloomy music]

10:54.343 --> 10:56.207
♪

10:56.241 --> 10:59.555
Wanna bring it back to
my camp, that's for sure.

10:59.589 --> 11:01.212
♪

11:01.246 --> 11:03.248
I'm really grateful right now.

11:03.283 --> 11:04.836
Really needed this.

11:04.871 --> 11:06.666
♪

11:06.700 --> 11:09.910
Oh, [bleep].

11:09.945 --> 11:11.705
You gotta be kidding me.

11:11.740 --> 11:15.157
I [bleep] stabbed myself
with my arrow.

11:15.191 --> 11:17.642
I can feel blood
dripping down my leg.

11:21.750 --> 11:22.889
- Oh, [bleep].

11:22.923 --> 11:25.098
I can't believe
I just cut myself.

11:25.132 --> 11:28.446
My arrow jammed into my leg,
ripped my pants,

11:28.480 --> 11:31.725
and I can feel blood
dripping down my leg.

11:31.760 --> 11:32.726
[sighs]

11:32.761 --> 11:34.521
I gotta take a look.

11:34.555 --> 11:37.110
Gosh, okay.
Here we go.

11:37.144 --> 11:40.147
Oh, [bleep]!

11:40.182 --> 11:41.804
Jeez.

11:41.839 --> 11:44.496
It's freakin' deep.

11:44.531 --> 11:48.742
Ah...that's [bleep] bad.

11:48.777 --> 11:51.020
I gotta tend to this.

11:51.055 --> 11:52.539
[moans]

11:52.573 --> 11:54.299
♪

11:54.334 --> 11:57.751
Yeah, I'll deal with
the tripod first

11:57.786 --> 12:01.272
before I tend to a flesh wound.

12:01.306 --> 12:04.689
It looks like it needs
serious care.

12:04.724 --> 12:06.208
[groans]

12:06.242 --> 12:08.106
Okay.

12:08.141 --> 12:09.107
[grunts]

12:09.142 --> 12:10.868
[inhales sharply]

12:10.902 --> 12:13.594
I'm just gonna...

12:13.629 --> 12:15.217
[grunts softly]

12:15.251 --> 12:17.806
hold that on there.

12:17.840 --> 12:21.188
Let me tie this thing...

12:21.223 --> 12:24.433
I don't want blood all over
this though, but...

12:24.467 --> 12:26.331
just till I can get
a fire going

12:26.366 --> 12:30.784
and then be able to be warm
and do this.

12:30.819 --> 12:34.754
♪

12:34.788 --> 12:37.101
Oh, come on, striker.

12:37.135 --> 12:38.792
♪

12:38.827 --> 12:41.174
Aw, man, my hands hurt.

12:41.208 --> 12:42.313
[blows]

12:42.347 --> 12:48.181
♪

12:48.215 --> 12:50.148
Oh.

12:50.183 --> 12:52.633
Thank you.

12:52.668 --> 12:54.912
Bless you.

12:54.946 --> 12:56.603
Oh.

12:56.637 --> 12:58.605
[grunts]

12:58.639 --> 13:01.435
Okay, um...

13:01.470 --> 13:03.679
[grunts]

13:03.713 --> 13:04.956
[bleep].

13:06.544 --> 13:09.374
[grunts]
Like a hole in my leg.

13:09.409 --> 13:11.445
Literally, I don't know
how deep it is.

13:11.480 --> 13:14.138
♪

13:14.172 --> 13:16.588
Ow.

13:16.623 --> 13:19.350
I think it looks pretty clean.

13:19.384 --> 13:23.457
It looks like blood, not dirt.

13:23.492 --> 13:27.668
I need some butterfly bandages
quite freakin' clearly.

13:27.703 --> 13:30.361
I'm just making
tons of mistakes.

13:30.395 --> 13:34.537
Out here, you can't do that
kind of stuff to yourself.

13:34.572 --> 13:37.195
You gotta pace yourself
and at the same time,

13:37.230 --> 13:40.992
you gotta just be on it
with everything.

13:41.027 --> 13:43.546
No mistakes...

13:43.581 --> 13:46.895
'cause the next one
will send me home.

13:46.929 --> 13:50.657
Okay, kinda sad to report...

13:50.691 --> 13:53.902
but this is how
I'm walking right now.

13:53.936 --> 13:55.835
Little limpy.

13:55.869 --> 13:59.045
Hi, animals.
Wait for me.

13:59.079 --> 14:00.494
I'm coming.

14:01.841 --> 14:05.085
Like, what the hell, dude?

14:05.120 --> 14:08.088
[suspenseful music]

14:08.123 --> 14:15.130
♪

14:17.201 --> 14:20.135
[chimes ringing]

14:20.169 --> 14:27.176
♪

14:29.178 --> 14:32.147
[birds chirping]

14:32.181 --> 14:39.119
♪

14:44.814 --> 14:45.850
[bow vibrates]

14:47.576 --> 14:49.681
- Shot right over it.

14:49.716 --> 14:56.723
♪

15:01.383 --> 15:05.870
Haven't seen anything
to hunt other than squirrel.

15:05.905 --> 15:08.252
And I've only taken
one squirrel

15:08.286 --> 15:10.599
the entire time
I've been here.

15:30.032 --> 15:32.241
We need to get
a lot more insulation

15:32.276 --> 15:35.106
to at least bide us
until the snows comes.

15:35.141 --> 15:36.728
♪

15:36.763 --> 15:39.973
My thought was on insulating
the shelter

15:40.008 --> 15:43.839
was I was gonna start
harvesting...

15:43.873 --> 15:47.636
some of this mossy,
duffy stuff

15:47.670 --> 15:50.259
and start placing it
over the top of

15:50.294 --> 15:52.365
these spruce bows
on the shelter.

15:52.399 --> 15:55.437
Now that it's pretty much
completely covered in spruce,

15:55.471 --> 15:57.404
that should close up
some of the gaps

15:57.439 --> 16:00.304
and give it
some insulated properties.

16:00.338 --> 16:02.064
Well, let's see how this works.

16:02.099 --> 16:03.617
♪

16:03.652 --> 16:07.035
[grunting]

16:07.069 --> 16:11.867
The best part about
being out here is the freedom.

16:11.901 --> 16:16.113
This journey represents
a higher level of freedom,

16:16.147 --> 16:18.667
a simpler life...

16:18.701 --> 16:21.463
a much more stress-free life.

16:21.497 --> 16:26.088
In a lot of ways
it's way easier

16:26.123 --> 16:28.297
than life in the modern world.

16:28.332 --> 16:29.609
♪

16:29.643 --> 16:33.371
All right, all right,
all right.

16:33.406 --> 16:36.823
Yeah.
Hoo.

16:36.857 --> 16:40.033
While there will always be
a need

16:40.068 --> 16:43.726
for maintenance and upkeep...

16:43.761 --> 16:47.420
with the exception of the door,

16:47.454 --> 16:50.112
my shelter is essentially done.

16:51.907 --> 16:53.184
[groans]

16:55.324 --> 16:58.879
Yeah.
Heck am I gonna do now?

16:58.914 --> 17:00.226
[grunts]

17:01.537 --> 17:04.506
[tense music]

17:04.540 --> 17:11.547
♪

17:16.069 --> 17:19.486
- Interesting thing about
this island...

17:19.521 --> 17:22.489
the wind is blowing in
a direction that's suitable

17:22.524 --> 17:24.077
to call a moose.

17:26.045 --> 17:29.669
And you can see when they cross
that whole muddy peninsula,

17:29.703 --> 17:32.948
so if they're coming
you'll know ahead of time.

17:32.982 --> 17:34.846
♪

17:34.881 --> 17:36.434
I made a birch bark
moose call.

17:36.469 --> 17:39.161
The moose call just imitates
a female

17:39.196 --> 17:40.956
that's ready to mate.

17:40.990 --> 17:44.546
If you're a super avid
moose hunter...

17:44.580 --> 17:46.410
♪

17:46.444 --> 17:47.825
Then don't be too critical.

17:47.859 --> 17:49.827
I'm no pro, but...

17:52.416 --> 17:55.419
[moaning]

18:00.941 --> 18:03.944
[moaning continues]

18:08.915 --> 18:11.504
All right, give that
a few minutes now.

18:12.608 --> 18:15.335
And head back.

18:15.370 --> 18:22.377
♪

18:23.412 --> 18:27.071
The crows are going crazy,

18:27.106 --> 18:30.143
which sometimes they do when
there's a bear walking around.

18:30.178 --> 18:33.146
[crows cawing]

18:33.181 --> 18:35.666
[can tumbles]

18:35.700 --> 18:36.943
Oh, crap.

18:36.977 --> 18:39.048
My early warning system.

18:39.083 --> 18:43.501
♪

18:43.536 --> 18:45.262
I don't see anything
over there,

18:45.296 --> 18:48.368
but I'm gonna be on my toes.

18:48.403 --> 18:50.025
♪

18:50.059 --> 18:51.337
[grunts]

18:51.371 --> 18:54.098
♪

18:54.133 --> 18:56.031
[whispers]
Oh, my God.

18:56.065 --> 18:59.034
[exciting music]

18:59.068 --> 19:06.145
♪

19:07.905 --> 19:14.912
♪

19:26.544 --> 19:27.787
[bow thuds]

19:30.169 --> 19:31.480
Damn.

19:31.515 --> 19:33.965
♪

19:34.000 --> 19:35.795
Estimated his distance,

19:35.829 --> 19:39.730
shot and dropped it
right between his legs.

19:39.764 --> 19:41.249
Oh, man.

19:43.251 --> 19:44.769
Such a downer.

19:44.804 --> 19:46.323
♪

19:46.357 --> 19:49.602
I'm gonna think about that one
for a long time.

19:49.636 --> 19:51.466
Everything worked as planned.

19:51.500 --> 19:55.159
The early warning system
was loud.

19:55.194 --> 19:56.609
If I would have had two shots,

19:56.643 --> 19:58.818
I would have gotten the moose
for sure,

19:58.852 --> 20:01.234
but you don't get two shots.

20:01.269 --> 20:04.893
Not to mention, when I hurry,
I only grabbed one arrow.

20:04.927 --> 20:06.964
So even if I would have had
time to reload,

20:06.998 --> 20:11.486
which I may have,
I did not have another arrow.

20:11.520 --> 20:12.935
♪

20:12.970 --> 20:16.422
I don't get to see that moose
again until the show airs.

20:16.456 --> 20:17.906
That's pretty annoying.

20:17.940 --> 20:24.947
♪

20:38.927 --> 20:40.515
- I was thinking last night

20:40.549 --> 20:43.242
as I was working on the cabin
into the dark,

20:43.276 --> 20:47.280
but after this experience,
depending on how long I stay...

20:47.315 --> 20:51.284
hopefully it'll be,
let's say 94 days,

20:51.319 --> 20:55.323
that I thought it would be
very amusing to get made up

20:55.357 --> 20:58.326
"I survived 94 days alone
in the arctic,

20:58.360 --> 21:01.398
and all I got was
this stupid T-shirt."

21:01.432 --> 21:03.331
I think I'd rather have it
say: "I sur-thrived,"

21:03.365 --> 21:05.402
but I'm not sure--I'm not sure
that what

21:05.436 --> 21:07.473
I'm doing is "sur-thriving."

21:07.507 --> 21:09.337
Truth be told, I think
I'm more "surviving."

21:09.371 --> 21:11.753
I think "sur-thriving"
would involve food.

21:11.787 --> 21:14.687
[laughs]

21:14.721 --> 21:16.965
Yeah, food has first priority,

21:16.999 --> 21:21.141
especially while I still have
a little bit of energy left.

21:21.176 --> 21:24.144
Feels like a good time to do
the further-ranging missions.

21:24.179 --> 21:27.147
[serene music]

21:27.182 --> 21:31.324
It's definitely the arctic.
Not fooling around here.

21:31.359 --> 21:33.084
I mean, it's why I put
so much energy

21:33.119 --> 21:36.502
towards my shelter right away,
rather than food.

21:36.536 --> 21:38.780
But now I am hungry as hell.

21:38.814 --> 21:40.437
♪

21:40.471 --> 21:41.748
There's crowberries here.

21:41.783 --> 21:44.303
I'd love to stop and pick them
and have a little breakfast.

21:45.442 --> 21:47.547
Crowberries are definitely
changing.

21:47.582 --> 21:50.585
The foliage is getting
more orange-y.

21:50.619 --> 21:52.828
And I feel like the berries
are gonna be drying up,

21:52.863 --> 21:55.279
so I'm trying to fill
my gullet now.

21:55.314 --> 21:56.280
Check it out.

21:56.315 --> 21:58.144
Not a bad handful of
crowberries.

22:01.596 --> 22:05.910
All right, that feels like
about all I can manage.

22:05.945 --> 22:07.360
I think maybe it's because
my body

22:07.395 --> 22:10.674
actually really wants
animal food.

22:10.708 --> 22:14.263
I'm really hoping for red meat
and large game.

22:14.298 --> 22:18.026
I think that's the only real
long-term sustainable strategy

22:18.060 --> 22:19.545
for being out here.

22:19.579 --> 22:21.305
[whispers]

22:21.340 --> 22:26.655
♪

22:29.589 --> 22:31.729
It's a very good sign.

22:31.764 --> 22:34.594
Check out this path

22:34.629 --> 22:37.459
through the reeds,
out to the lake.

22:37.494 --> 22:39.185
And then right here,

22:39.219 --> 22:43.776
a pile of freshly chewed
alder branches.

22:43.810 --> 22:44.811
If I could get a moose,

22:44.846 --> 22:48.056
it would turn everything
around.

22:48.090 --> 22:51.439
[whispering]
This is prime moose habitat.

22:51.473 --> 22:53.579
But I'm gonna keep looking
along the shore

22:53.613 --> 22:55.443
and see what I can see.

22:57.445 --> 23:00.482
[suspenseful music]

23:00.517 --> 23:07.524
♪

23:15.808 --> 23:19.812
♪

23:19.846 --> 23:21.503
She flew off.

23:21.538 --> 23:24.437
♪

23:24.472 --> 23:27.785
And I don't know where
it ended up.

23:27.820 --> 23:29.408
♪

23:29.442 --> 23:31.202
I was getting close to
my home base

23:31.237 --> 23:33.066
and heard this flutter
of wings

23:33.101 --> 23:36.069
and, up in this little tree,
flew a grouse.

23:36.104 --> 23:38.140
I crept around closer,
and I took the shot

23:38.175 --> 23:39.279
with a broadhead.

23:39.314 --> 23:41.212
And I totally hit her.

23:41.247 --> 23:44.457
You can see,
went right through her.

23:44.492 --> 23:48.392
Covered in feathers,
covered in blood.

23:48.427 --> 23:51.809
She flew off and now is dying
in the woods somewhere,

23:51.844 --> 23:54.156
and I need to find her.

23:54.191 --> 23:58.022
But hard to find a very
camouflaged, wounded bird

23:58.057 --> 24:01.681
in a landscape she is designed
to blend in with.

24:01.716 --> 24:03.890
Hope upon hope that I can
find her and retrieve her,

24:03.925 --> 24:07.584
'cause that would be
such a shame and such a waste.

24:07.618 --> 24:10.483
And the hunger is definitely
starting to get to me,

24:10.518 --> 24:12.830
'cause I am feeling
a little desperate

24:12.865 --> 24:18.698
around the food situation.

24:18.733 --> 24:22.253
- Just shot my first
spruce grouse.

24:22.288 --> 24:25.118
The arrow went right through
that entire bird.

24:25.153 --> 24:27.155
♪

24:27.189 --> 24:30.848
Oh, it's so hard
to be so close

24:30.883 --> 24:34.024
to having gotten a grouse.

24:34.058 --> 24:36.095
Please...

24:36.129 --> 24:38.269
please, please let me find you.

24:38.304 --> 24:41.480
♪

24:41.514 --> 24:45.932
There's so much habitat
to cover.

24:45.967 --> 24:48.141
♪

24:48.176 --> 24:51.490
She was white and dark gray.

24:51.524 --> 24:55.494
I'm gonna go around
the edges now,

24:55.528 --> 24:58.462
and then I'll go through
the middle again.

24:58.497 --> 24:59.912
♪

24:59.946 --> 25:03.467
I'm pretty physically tough,
and I don't give up easily,

25:03.502 --> 25:05.883
but I'm working really hard.

25:05.918 --> 25:08.576
I'm very active
every single day.

25:08.610 --> 25:10.854
I'm doing a lot that
burns calories

25:10.888 --> 25:13.926
and the cumulative effect
of that is

25:13.960 --> 25:17.343
burning through all of
my body's stored calories.

25:17.377 --> 25:20.760
♪

25:22.935 --> 25:25.696
Just don't know how far
a grouse can go wounded.

25:25.731 --> 25:29.044
I know a bear can run
30 yards after

25:29.079 --> 25:30.425
it's been shot in the heart.

25:30.459 --> 25:32.151
[gasps]
There she is.

25:32.185 --> 25:35.050
Oh, my God.
Thank God.

25:35.085 --> 25:37.639
Oh.
Oh, my God.

25:37.674 --> 25:39.330
I found her.

25:39.365 --> 25:40.539
♪

25:40.573 --> 25:43.438
Oh, I want to save
every piece of her.

25:43.472 --> 25:46.096
She is so gorgeous.

25:46.130 --> 25:47.615
[whimpers]

25:47.649 --> 25:50.134
So grateful.

25:50.169 --> 25:54.276
I've been--I've been coming
to this whole experience

25:54.311 --> 25:56.589
from such a good place;

25:56.624 --> 25:59.454
from a place of just
really wanting to live in

25:59.488 --> 26:02.008
deep connection with the land.

26:02.043 --> 26:04.908
So I've been so conscious
and so prayerful

26:04.942 --> 26:06.875
and so communicative,

26:06.910 --> 26:08.705
but I've been starving.

26:08.739 --> 26:10.776
[laughs]

26:10.810 --> 26:13.330
So it is so gratifying now

26:13.364 --> 26:17.817
to feel--to feel the reward.

26:17.852 --> 26:20.337
[sighs]
Yep.

26:20.371 --> 26:21.372
[laughs]

26:21.407 --> 26:24.375
I've got grouse feathers
smeared in my tears.

26:24.410 --> 26:25.860
[laughs]

26:25.894 --> 26:28.103
Oh, God.

26:28.138 --> 26:30.105
Hoo--wow.

26:30.140 --> 26:33.522
What a freakin' morning!

26:33.557 --> 26:36.525
[tranquil music]

26:36.560 --> 26:43.567
♪

26:52.783 --> 26:55.683
- Fishing, fishing, fishing.

26:55.717 --> 26:59.687
Let's do some catching today.
We're not just fishing.

27:03.449 --> 27:06.279
[splashing]

27:06.314 --> 27:07.626
[grunts]

27:09.006 --> 27:10.836
[grunts]
[bleep].

27:13.045 --> 27:14.460
[yells]

27:18.291 --> 27:22.779
Getting wet was not part of
my fishing plan.

27:25.713 --> 27:29.199
Well, I'm here now...

27:29.233 --> 27:30.787
so I'm fishing.

27:30.821 --> 27:33.824
[panting]

27:35.861 --> 27:37.379
[grunts]

27:37.414 --> 27:40.382
[foreboding music]

27:40.417 --> 27:41.798
♪

27:41.832 --> 27:46.009
Fishing is beginning to be
a point of frustration.

27:46.043 --> 27:49.495
They've definitely suddenly
dropped off.

27:49.529 --> 27:52.084
It's partially because of
the spawn.

27:52.118 --> 27:54.120
Oftentimes
when fish are spawning,

27:54.155 --> 27:58.021
they're not really interested
in much else.

27:58.055 --> 28:02.128
Not seeing a single fish
swimming by, around

28:02.163 --> 28:03.198
in the area.

28:03.233 --> 28:05.166
No little fish, no nothing.

28:07.237 --> 28:09.791
Still got berries to forage...

28:09.826 --> 28:12.069
squirrels to hunt.

28:12.104 --> 28:15.970
♪

28:16.004 --> 28:17.316
In the last 16 days,

28:17.350 --> 28:19.801
I've had one fish,
one squirrel,

28:19.836 --> 28:21.078
and a lot of berries.

28:21.113 --> 28:22.321
♪

28:22.355 --> 28:26.014
Hello, great big ol' berry
hiding down there.

28:26.049 --> 28:28.568
I think my body's getting to
the point where

28:28.603 --> 28:31.123
berries alone may not
be enough.

28:31.157 --> 28:35.265
♪

28:39.545 --> 28:44.170
♪

28:44.205 --> 28:46.759
I'm enjoying the experience,

28:46.794 --> 28:50.763
but at what point is it
not worth it?

28:50.798 --> 28:55.043
Is the risk to my own body
and future health

28:55.078 --> 28:59.047
so great that I need to
call it and go home?

28:59.082 --> 29:01.222
♪

29:01.256 --> 29:02.844
What is that point?

29:02.879 --> 29:05.813
♪

29:08.229 --> 29:09.678
That's long enough.

29:13.959 --> 29:16.927
[pensive music]

29:16.962 --> 29:19.654
♪

29:19.688 --> 29:22.761
I'd say what's keeping me here
at this point...

29:22.795 --> 29:24.763
♪

29:24.797 --> 29:28.559
Is my fear from going home.

29:28.594 --> 29:32.011
My fear...to be back...

29:32.046 --> 29:33.806
♪

29:33.841 --> 29:36.878
In that mundane world.

29:36.913 --> 29:39.536
Nine to fives,
and punching clocks,

29:39.570 --> 29:42.919
and being stressed out
over other people's problems.

29:42.953 --> 29:44.196
♪

29:44.230 --> 29:47.820
Not so hard before
you've tasted freedom...

29:47.855 --> 29:52.825
♪

29:52.860 --> 29:56.725
But definitely hard to go
back into the cage

29:56.760 --> 30:00.799
after you've flown free
for a long time.

30:09.359 --> 30:12.327
[trees whooshing]

30:12.362 --> 30:15.744
- Ooh, it's windy and cold.

30:15.779 --> 30:17.746
So I'm just gonna hang out
in here

30:17.781 --> 30:21.612
and eat my amazing
grouse-iness.

30:21.647 --> 30:22.613
♪

30:22.648 --> 30:26.100
Yes.
Look at that.

30:26.134 --> 30:27.929
That, my friends,

30:27.964 --> 30:31.105
is a good-sized piece of meat.

30:31.139 --> 30:32.106
Wow.

30:32.140 --> 30:34.694
And here are heart,

30:34.729 --> 30:37.042
this is all chunks of
breast meat,

30:37.076 --> 30:41.184
this is liver,
and then there is the leg.

30:41.218 --> 30:43.220
Hoo-ray.

30:43.255 --> 30:46.534
May this motivate me
to hunt better,

30:46.568 --> 30:49.778
so I can eat like this
every day.

30:49.813 --> 30:51.470
♪

30:51.504 --> 30:55.854
Mm.
Oh, my goodness.

30:55.888 --> 30:58.132
Oh, that is so satisfying.

30:58.166 --> 31:00.375
This was the tipping point,

31:00.410 --> 31:02.136
and now I'll be bringing in
the game.

31:02.170 --> 31:04.276
And maybe now the grouse
are showing up.

31:04.310 --> 31:05.794
♪

31:05.829 --> 31:08.245
Now that I am fully fortified

31:08.280 --> 31:10.696
with delicious meat
in my belly,

31:10.730 --> 31:14.907
I wanna be out exploring
that new area...

31:14.942 --> 31:15.908
with my bow.

31:15.943 --> 31:18.324
And time is a-wastin'.

31:18.359 --> 31:21.327
[ominous music]

31:21.362 --> 31:28.369
♪

31:40.795 --> 31:43.763
[water whooshing]

31:43.798 --> 31:50.115
♪

31:50.149 --> 31:51.668
- Good morning.

31:54.222 --> 31:57.881
[moans]
Welcome to day 19.

32:02.092 --> 32:04.543
[moans]

32:07.304 --> 32:09.858
It is a cold morning.

32:09.893 --> 32:14.656
And I think...going on
a roam.

32:15.968 --> 32:20.179
I'll go and see what lies
past the lake.

32:20.214 --> 32:22.906
[serene music]

32:22.941 --> 32:25.529
With fishing
not producing anything

32:25.564 --> 32:29.809
and only so much time left
that I can forage berries,

32:29.844 --> 32:33.330
it's becoming fairly evident
that I am going to have to

32:33.365 --> 32:35.677
turn to active hunting...

32:35.712 --> 32:36.885
♪

32:36.920 --> 32:39.233
Packing a good load today.

32:39.267 --> 32:41.407
Heading up the hill again.

32:41.442 --> 32:43.858
And really need to try to get
a better understanding

32:43.892 --> 32:45.273
of my area.

32:45.308 --> 32:47.206
Nothing I'm doing is working.

32:47.241 --> 32:50.382
I need to find some way
to procure something to eat.

32:50.416 --> 32:54.696
♪

33:01.669 --> 33:04.637
[domineering music]

33:04.672 --> 33:11.230
♪

33:11.265 --> 33:13.992
I geared up for a long run
to go check out

33:14.026 --> 33:15.752
the furthest reaches of
my area,

33:15.786 --> 33:18.030
and I don't have the energy
for it.

33:18.065 --> 33:19.618
♪

33:19.652 --> 33:22.276
I'm basically in a battle
of attrition

33:22.310 --> 33:24.519
and a starvation game.

33:24.554 --> 33:29.421
And I don't know if it's worth
putting myself at risk.

33:29.455 --> 33:36.462
♪

33:38.361 --> 33:39.500
[radio beeps]

33:39.534 --> 33:46.541
♪

33:47.715 --> 33:49.061
Be sure, Ray.

33:49.096 --> 33:56.103
♪

34:00.797 --> 34:02.247
Yep.

34:06.941 --> 34:08.115
[radio beeps]

34:14.121 --> 34:16.951
This is Ray.

34:16.985 --> 34:20.541
I am officially tapping out.

34:20.575 --> 34:23.544
[solemn music]

34:23.578 --> 34:30.585
♪

34:43.840 --> 34:46.429
I've done all I can here.

34:46.463 --> 34:49.466
I've enjoyed this experience.

34:49.501 --> 34:53.677
And I wanna remember it as
something to be enjoyed.

34:53.712 --> 34:58.165
♪

34:58.199 --> 35:01.064
Making that call was
very difficult.

35:01.099 --> 35:03.308
You feel pressure to go out

35:03.342 --> 35:07.139
having given every last ounce,

35:07.174 --> 35:08.658
but it was logistical.

35:08.692 --> 35:10.556
I couldn't find enough to eat.

35:10.591 --> 35:13.870
And the prospect of finding
anything more

35:13.904 --> 35:17.149
than what I'm getting seemed
very unlikely.

35:17.184 --> 35:20.980
So why put my body at
significant risk?

35:21.015 --> 35:22.948
I'm feeling sad about leaving,

35:22.982 --> 35:25.502
like I've let my wife down,
myself down.

35:25.537 --> 35:28.747
I expected to be out here
quite a bit longer,

35:28.781 --> 35:31.888
and I'm feeling anxiety about
going back.

35:31.922 --> 35:34.615
This journey showed me
true freedom.

35:34.649 --> 35:36.824
That gave me
a better understanding of

35:36.858 --> 35:38.757
the modern world.

35:38.791 --> 35:41.932
It's just like anything else.
It's what you make of it.

35:41.967 --> 35:45.039
♪

35:48.663 --> 35:51.666
[dramatic music] - When you're pretty hungry,
time goes really slowly.

35:51.701 --> 35:54.048
So I'd really be happy
to catch a fish,

35:54.082 --> 35:56.913
but takes you all day,

35:56.947 --> 35:59.571
and you don't get anything.

35:59.605 --> 36:02.125
It's just more fun to snare
and hunt

36:02.160 --> 36:06.025
than to stand by the shore
like a moron

36:06.060 --> 36:10.616
for hours and hours.

36:10.651 --> 36:13.792
But you gotta figure it out,

36:13.826 --> 36:17.796
'cause there's only so many
bunnies to snare around here.

36:17.830 --> 36:21.351
♪

36:21.386 --> 36:24.768
Oh, man.
All these snares are empty.

36:24.803 --> 36:26.356
♪

36:26.391 --> 36:28.496
Might have to move 'em.

36:28.531 --> 36:30.291
The word must have got out

36:30.326 --> 36:34.157
that an assassin is
on the loose in the area.

36:34.192 --> 36:37.471
Even the moose are sort of
on to me.

36:37.505 --> 36:40.370
I'm mad at myself for
missing the first one.

36:40.405 --> 36:43.339
That was the big screw up
on my part.

36:43.373 --> 36:44.512
♪

36:44.547 --> 36:45.548
[grunts]

36:45.582 --> 36:49.241
Nature is a beauti--brutal
place at times.

36:49.276 --> 36:53.349
That's why...we're just
part of it.

36:54.591 --> 36:57.801
My dad went through
so much suffering.

36:57.836 --> 37:00.701
He had diabetes,
amputated his leg.

37:00.735 --> 37:03.669
Couple years later,
they amputated his other leg.

37:03.704 --> 37:07.535
And then he lost
all the feeling in his hands.

37:07.570 --> 37:10.400
But somehow he always--very
good at maintaining,

37:10.435 --> 37:14.439
like, a positive
and super encouraging attitude

37:14.473 --> 37:16.026
through the whole thing.

37:16.061 --> 37:19.409
He had that joy in him
up until his last breath.

37:19.444 --> 37:21.411
So it was a lesson that

37:21.446 --> 37:24.034
you couldn't buy with
any amount of money.

37:24.069 --> 37:25.070
[chuckles]

37:25.104 --> 37:27.900
Hopefully,
when the tragedy comes,

37:27.935 --> 37:31.490
our imprint on the world
will be enough to say that

37:31.525 --> 37:34.217
it was--it was worth it.

37:34.252 --> 37:36.909
♪

37:44.641 --> 37:47.299
Nah, I should go do something
more productive.

37:47.334 --> 37:49.681
Could build, you know, like,
a reindeer fence,

37:49.715 --> 37:53.340
kind of funneling
potential moose to stay

37:53.374 --> 37:55.376
near the water.

37:55.411 --> 37:58.552
I'm so desperate for places
to hunt things,

37:58.586 --> 37:59.760
it's worth a shot.

37:59.794 --> 38:00.968
[grunts]

38:13.083 --> 38:14.913
See, when you're chopping
these trees down,

38:14.947 --> 38:17.225
you don't wanna chop 'em
from both sides

38:17.260 --> 38:18.296
so they fall off.

38:18.330 --> 38:20.332
You just wanna...

38:20.367 --> 38:25.061
maybe hit it on this side to
weaken the fibers a bit.

38:25.095 --> 38:28.789
And then just give it one chop.

38:28.823 --> 38:32.171
Fall it over and it'll hold
like that.

38:32.206 --> 38:34.691
We don't need to even set
this one.

38:53.054 --> 38:54.124
Here you go.

38:54.159 --> 38:56.334
You're coming down this trail,
there's a moose.

38:56.368 --> 39:00.372
So, like, "Oh, man,
trees in the way."

39:00.407 --> 39:03.064
No big lazy moose wants

39:03.099 --> 39:05.826
to jump around,

39:05.860 --> 39:10.002
so there you go.

39:10.037 --> 39:11.003
That's a start.

39:11.038 --> 39:12.419
I don't wanna burn
too much energy,

39:12.453 --> 39:14.869
but I'll come do more.

39:14.904 --> 39:16.043
♪

39:16.077 --> 39:18.666
Hopefully,
I get another chance.

39:18.701 --> 39:21.151
I have that giant weight
on my shoulder

39:21.186 --> 39:23.326
all the time that
I'm gonna starve.

39:23.361 --> 39:26.329
[foreboding music]

39:26.364 --> 39:33.371
♪

39:36.995 --> 39:41.240
Well, couldn't sleep very well,
'cause I was thinking all night

39:41.275 --> 39:43.967
about what I should do.

39:44.002 --> 39:47.074
The only thing I can really do
is take my snares that are

39:47.108 --> 39:51.147
being less productive and move
them into better spots.

39:51.181 --> 39:55.634
♪

39:55.669 --> 39:58.534
Think a lot of the snares
that I have that are out

39:58.568 --> 40:01.951
probably no longer
gonna catch anything.

40:01.985 --> 40:03.401
♪

40:03.435 --> 40:05.023
[groans]

40:06.783 --> 40:07.853
It's not cool.

40:10.649 --> 40:13.618
[suspenseful music]

40:13.652 --> 40:20.659
♪

40:24.180 --> 40:25.181
♪

40:25.215 --> 40:27.597
- The wind is
really picking up.

40:27.632 --> 40:29.288
I'm just so exposed right now.

40:29.323 --> 40:32.084
I need to get the hell off of
this rock.

40:32.119 --> 40:35.122
- [groaning]

40:35.156 --> 40:37.158
[bleep].
[moans]

40:37.193 --> 40:39.471
- My heart's pumping so fast
right now.

40:39.506 --> 40:42.267
Just hit that moose.

40:42.301 --> 40:44.821
Some good bubbly blood
on there.

40:44.856 --> 40:47.514
- I heard something screaming
outside.

40:47.548 --> 40:48.860
♪

40:48.894 --> 40:49.861
I'm just gonna go out...

40:49.895 --> 40:52.242
[animal roars]
[bleep].

40:52.277 --> 40:53.278
♪
